Real Money for Photorealism

John Kacere, Untitled (with White Slip), from 1989, at Gratin Gallery

In the late 1960s and early 1970s, a loose group of painters began creating=
 images that mimicked the flatness and reflections on surfaces captured by =
photographs. The critical and market appraisal for these painters, who beca=
me known as the photorealists, has waxed and waned for some time. Recently,=
 however, there have been stirrings on the market side. Richard Estes, the =
best-known among the group, made three of his four highest prices at auctio=
n last year. Work by Robert Bechtle, who died in 2020, was shown ( https://=
www.gladstonegallery.com/exhibition/10771/robert-bechtle-2023/installation-=
views?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F17%2F24%29&utm_conten=
t=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F17%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&u=
tm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) at
Gladstone Gallery in Chelsea last year, too. (Posthumous shows are usually =
more directional, or a sign of support for an artist=E2=80=99s estate.) A s=
mall diner still life by Ralph Goings was sold for more than twice the esti=
mate in October at Sotheby=E2=80=99s. A much larger painting of a ketchup b=
ottle ( https://www.bonhams.com/auction/29521/lot/10A/ralph-goings-1928-201=
6-ketchup-close-up-44-x-60-in-1117-x-1525-cm-painted-in-1990/?utm_campaign=
=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F17%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+S=
