The titanic struggle for control of Artnet, the media and data company that=
 provides a pivot point for the entire art market, was scheduled to come to=
 a head at tomorrow=E2=80=99s annual general meeting. Artnet is controlled =
by the Neuendorf family, which owns 26 percent of the company=E2=80=99s sha=
res. A slightly larger percentage of the shares, which are traded on the Ge=
rman stock exchange, are owned by Rudiger Weng, who=E2=80=99s been campaign=
ing to win a seat on the three-person board of directors. Weng believes he =
finally has the votes, which would subsequently allow him to oust C.E.O. Ja=
cob Pabst, the 52-year-old son of Hans Neuendorf, the company=E2=80=99s 87-=
year-old founder. But late last week, the meeting was canceled without warn=
ing.

This isn=E2=80=99t the first time the Neuendorf family has used delays and =
deflection to retain
control of the company. In 2012, when another group of investors were tryin=
g to grab the reins, Neuendorf replaced himself as C.E.O. with his son. Sin=
ce then, his daughter and two other sons have taken up executive roles=E2=
=80=94though one son has since left the company.

