In 2020, the company=E2=80=99s annual general meeting=E2=80=94a requirement=
 for listed firms in Germany=E2=80=94was postponed because Pabst claimed to=
 be ill. By that point, however, Weng had already begun to amass his substa=
ntial position in the company. He agitated for change in 2021, 2022, and 20=
23=E2=80=94but he couldn=E2=80=99t convince enough shareholders to cross th=
e 50 percent threshold. Now, after delays in the release of the company=E2=
=80=99s 2023 financials and last week=E2=80=99s rug pull, investors may fin=
ally be getting fed up.

The curious thing about last week=E2=80=99s canceled A.G.M. was the reason.=
 Instead of putting off the investors=E2=80=99 forum by claiming illness=E2=
=80=94which might have been hard to believe, but also hard to refute=E2=80=
=94the company said the delay was being caused by a problem with their audi=
tors, the same firm that produced the 2023 financials. =E2=80=9CThe general
meeting is being canceled,=E2=80=9D wrote Sophie Neuendorf, who handles the=
 company=E2=80=99s investor relations, =E2=80=9Cbecause the auditing firm [=
=E2=80=A6] has informed the Company that it is not available for a further =
audit.=E2=80=9D

This is somewhat unusual: Artnet got a new auditor last year, as German law=
 requires companies to swap auditors every five years. But it appears the n=
ew auditor is relinquishing its lucrative assignment after completing its r=
eview of Artnet=E2=80=99s 2023 financials. That report revealed several tra=
nsactions involving entities linked to family members, including the C.E.O.=
=E2=80=99s wife. The report also showed that Hans Neuendorf was still being=
 paid six-figure consulting fees, even though Weng told me he=E2=80=99d agr=
eed to stop after 2022. In addition, the auditors reported family members w=
ere paid $200,000 or more in related-party payments. There were also more t=
han $2 million in loans from both Galerie Neuendorf and an Artnet executive=
, as well as a private
party in New York.

So why did the auditors bail on Artnet? =E2=80=9CFollowing a complaint from=
 a key shareholder about the costs,=E2=80=9D the company said in a statemen=
t, =E2=80=9Cthe auditor informed Artnet=E2=80=99s management that they woul=
d not be able to carry out the audit for the 2024 financial year.=E2=80=9D =
Not surprisingly, Weng told me there=E2=80=99s more to the story. After all=
, he was the key shareholder. And he says the auditors had made it clear tw=
o months ago, in September, that they wouldn=E2=80=99t be sticking around.

Both sides agree that the audit wasn=E2=80=99t a pretty process. It =E2=80=
=9Ctook longer than anticipated,=E2=80=9D Artnet said in a statement, =E2=
=80=9Cas it was a first-time audit and presented additional challenges asso=
ciated with evaluating companies with a strong technological backbone.=E2=
=80=9D Weng said the process was delayed by Pabst=E2=80=99s foot-dragging a=
nd the board=E2=80=99s lack of cooperation, leading the auditors to submit =
invoices that were twice the estimate.

Both
sides were unhappy with the auditor=E2=80=99s fees. What happened next is d=
isputed. Weng says Pabst asked for his help with the auditors. =E2=80=9CI d=
iscussed the topic with him,=E2=80=9D Weng told me, =E2=80=9Cand he asked m=
e whether I could support him. Which I did with a letter to the auditors. A=
nd Jacob thanked me for doing it. I wanted to pave a way for him to negotia=
te a better price.=E2=80=9D But a representative of the company says Pabst =
never asked Weng to write to the auditors.

Awaiting a Showdown

It=E2=80=99s not at all clear why Artnet believes an issue with auditors wa=
s reason enough to cancel its shareholder meeting, let alone days before th=
e event. Even if you believe Artnet=E2=80=99s version of events, the audito=
rs quit three weeks ago. Why not inform shareholders right away, allowing t=
hem time to cancel plans to travel to Berlin?

Weng made clear in a statement last Thursday that he, too, was annoyed by t=
he delay, describing the cancellation as =E2=80=9Cunlawful and made in an a=
busive manner=E2=80=9D and revealing that his company has begun the legal p=
rocess to compel the meeting.

