It=E2=80=99s hard to know if Weng has the votes to change the company=E2=80=
=99s leadership, but the company=E2=80=99s stock price has gone up 30 perce=
nt in the last month, perhaps in anticipation of his showdown with the Neue=
ndorfs at the now-canceled meeting. The stock bump is a bit of a mystery ot=
herwise, considering that, last week, Artnet released a dour financial repo=
rt for the third quarter: Overall revenue fell 5.4 percent in the first nin=
e months of 2024, attributable to a 3.8 percent decline in media revenue an=
d a 5.8 percent drop in revenue from the sale of art. Gross profit was down=
 12 percent. Even in good years, Artnet has struggled to turn much of a pro=
fit=E2=80=94the source of much of the friction between the shareholders and=
 the Neuendorfs. But for the first nine months of 2024, operating income fe=
ll to negative =E2=82=AC1.35 million and operating cash flow was
down 45 percent.

Yet the stock price remains at a nine-month high, which isn=E2=80=99t great=
 news for the Neuendorfs, who previously enlisted passive investors to buy =
the company=E2=80=99s stock at depressed prices and vote with their bloc. I=
f the stock isn=E2=80=99t budging after the grim financials, it means that =
shareholders are sticking around; they haven=E2=80=99t given up on the comp=
any, but they may have given up on the Neuendorfs.

Endnotes=E2=80=A6

It=E2=80=99s likely that the elusive Artnet annual meeting will be reschedu=
led for early 2025. But I=E2=80=99m not holding my breath.

