          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">The titanic struggl=
e for control of Artnet, the media and data company that provides a pivot p=
oint for the entire art market, was scheduled to come to a head at tomorrow=
=E2=80=99s annual general meeting. Artnet is controlled by the <b>Neuendorf=
</b> family, which owns 26 percent of the company=E2=80=99s shares. A sligh=
tly larger percentage of the shares, which are traded on the German stock e=
xchange, are owned by <b>Rudiger Weng</b>, who=E2=80=99s been campaigning t=
o win a seat on the three-person board of directors. Weng believes he final=
ly has the votes, which would subsequently allow him to oust C.E.O.<b> Jaco=
b Pabst</b>, the 52-year-old son of <b>Hans Neuendorf</b>, the company=E2=
=80=99s 87-year-old founder. But late last week, the meeting was canceled w=
ithout warning. <br/><br/>This isn=E2=80=99t the first time the Neuendorf f=
amily has used delays and deflection to retain
control of the company. In 2012, when another group of investors were tryin=
g to grab the reins, Neuendorf replaced himself as C.E.O. with his son. Sin=
ce then, his daughter and two other sons have taken up executive roles=E2=
=80=94though one son has since left the company. <br/></td>
         </tr>
