         <tr class=3D"replica" name=3D"s2">
          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">In 2020, the compan=
y=E2=80=99s annual general meeting=E2=80=94a requirement for listed firms i=
n Germany=E2=80=94was postponed because Pabst claimed to be ill. By that po=
int, however, Weng had already begun to amass his substantial position in t=
he company. He agitated for change in 2021, 2022, and 2023=E2=80=94but he c=
ouldn=E2=80=99t convince enough shareholders to cross the 50 percent thresh=
old. Now, after delays in the release of the company=E2=80=99s 2023 financi=
als and last week=E2=80=99s rug pull, investors may finally be getting fed =
up. <br/><br/>The curious thing about last week=E2=80=99s canceled A.G.M. w=
as the reason. Instead of putting off the investors=E2=80=99 forum by claim=
ing illness=E2=80=94which might have been hard to believe, but also hard to=
 refute=E2=80=94the company said the delay was being caused by a problem wi=
th their auditors, the same firm that produced the 2023 financials. =E2=80=
=9CThe general
meeting is being canceled,=E2=80=9D wrote <b>Sophie</b> <b>Neuendorf</b>, w=
ho handles the company=E2=80=99s investor relations, =E2=80=9Cbecause the a=
uditing firm [=E2=80=A6] has informed the Company that it is not available =
for a further audit.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>This is somewhat unusual: Artnet go=
t a new auditor last year, as German law requires companies to swap auditor=
s every five years. But it appears the new auditor is relinquishing its luc=
rative assignment after completing its review of Artnet=E2=80=99s 2023 fina=
ncials. That report revealed several transactions involving entities linked=
 to family members, including the C.E.O.=E2=80=99s wife. The report also sh=
owed that Hans Neuendorf was still being paid six-figure consulting fees, e=
ven though Weng told me he=E2=80=99d agreed to stop after 2022. In addition=
, the auditors reported family members were paid $200,000 or more in relate=
d-party payments. There were also more than $2 million in loans from both G=
alerie Neuendorf and an Artnet executive, as well as a private
party in New York. <br/><br/>So why did the auditors bail on Artnet? =E2=80=
=9CFollowing a complaint from a key shareholder about the costs,=E2=80=9D t=
he company said in a statement, =E2=80=9Cthe auditor informed Artnet=E2=80=
=99s management that they would not be able to carry out the audit for the =
2024 financial year.=E2=80=9D Not surprisingly, Weng told me there=E2=80=99=
s more to the story. After all, he was the <i>key shareholder</i>. And he s=
ays the auditors had made it clear two months ago, in September, that they =
wouldn=E2=80=99t be sticking around. <br/><br/>Both sides agree that the au=
dit wasn=E2=80=99t a pretty process. It =E2=80=9Ctook longer than anticipat=
ed,=E2=80=9D Artnet said in a statement, =E2=80=9Cas it was a first-time au=
dit and presented additional challenges associated with evaluating companie=
s with a strong technological backbone.=E2=80=9D Weng said the process was =
delayed by Pabst=E2=80=99s foot-dragging and the board=E2=80=99s lack of co=
operation, leading the auditors to submit invoices that were twice the esti=
mate. <br/><br/>Both
sides were unhappy with the auditor=E2=80=99s fees. What happened next is d=
isputed. Weng says Pabst asked for his help with the auditors. =E2=80=9CI d=
iscussed the topic with him,=E2=80=9D Weng told me, =E2=80=9Cand he asked m=
e whether I could support him. Which I did with a letter to the auditors. A=
nd Jacob thanked me for doing it. I wanted to pave a way for him to negotia=
te a better price.=E2=80=9D But a representative of the company says Pabst =
never asked Weng to write to the auditors.<br/></td>
